[2026-03-13T14:39:21Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011iJi8dtrBvy4abcbRvR6Ru","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have a comprehensive understanding. Let me create the final report:\n\n## Thorough Project Exploration Report\n\nI have completed a comprehensive exploration of the Cloche project structure, conventions, and examples. Here's what I found:\n\n### 1. Project Files Under examples/ Directory\n\n**Examples present:**\n- `/workspace/examples/hello-world/` - Simple demonstration with build and flaky workflows\n- `/workspace/examples/ruby-calculator/` - Ruby project with implement/fix workflow\n- `/workspace/examples/gemini-browser/` - Rust project with design/implement workflow\n- `/workspace/examples/mini-redis/` - C project with design/implement workflow\n\n**Key files in each example:**\n- `develop.cloche` - Container workflow definition\n- `prompts/` - Prompt templates (implement.md, fix.md, design.md)\n- `scripts/` - Optional helper scripts (quality-check.py, etc.)\n- `Dockerfile` - Container image definition\n- `README.md` - Project documentation\n\n### 2. .cloche/ Directory at Project Root\n\nLocated at `/workspace/.cloche/`, the actual Cloche system's own workflows contain:\n- `develop.cloche` - Container workflow for the Cloche system itself\n- `host.cloche` - Host orchestration workflow with three phases (main)\n- `Dockerfile` - Base image extending `cloche-base:latest`\n- `attempt_count/` - Directory tracking retry attempts\n- `evolution/` - Snapshots of evolved workflows\n- `prompts/` - Prompt templates (implement.md, update-docs.md, fix.md)\n- `scripts/` - Host scripts (ready-tasks.sh, claim-task.sh, prepare-prompt.sh, merge-to-main.sh, cleanup-run.sh)\n- `history.log` - Execution history\n- `config.toml` - Configuration file\n\n### 3. Workflow DSL Documentation (docs/workflows.md)\n\n**Key concepts:**\n- **Workflow Locations**: `container` (runs in Docker) vs `host` (runs on host machine)\n- **Step Types** (inferred from content):\n  - `agent` - has `prompt` field (Claude Code or compatible agent)\n  - `script` - has `run` field (shell commands)\n  - `workflow` - has `workflow_name` field (host workflows only)\n- **Step Results**: Named outcomes declared per step (e.g., `success`, `fail`, `give-up`)\n- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result -> next-step` with optional output mappings\n- **Collect**: Fan-in for parallel branches: `collect all(...)` or `collect any(...)`\n- **Terminals**: Built-in `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) steps\n- **Host Workflow Phases**:\n  1. `list-tasks` - Discover available work (outputs JSONL)\n  2. `main` - Process a task (receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`)\n  3. `finalize` - Post-main cleanup (always runs)\n\n### 4. Domain Types (internal/domain/workflow.go)\n\n**Core Types:**\n```go\ntype Step struct {\n  Name    string\n  Type    StepType  // \"agent\", \"script\", \"workflow\"\n  Results []string  // declared result names\n  Config  map[string]string\n}\n\ntype Wire struct {\n  From      string\n  Result    string\n  To        string\n  OutputMap []OutputMapping  // env var mappings\n}\n\ntype OutputMapping struct {\n  EnvVar string\n  Path   OutputPath  // navigates JSON output\n}\n\ntype Workflow struct {\n  Name      string\n  Location  WorkflowLocation  // \"container\" or \"host\"\n  Steps     map[string]*Step\n  Wiring    []Wire\n  Collects  []Collect  // fan-in operations\n  EntryStep string\n  Config    map[string]string\n}\n```\n\n**Path expressions for output mappings:**\n- `output` - Raw output string\n- `output.field` - JSON object field\n- `output[N]` - Array index\n- `output.a.b.c` - Nested access\n- `output.items[0].name` - Mixed chaining\n\n### 5. Workflow Parser (internal/dsl/parser.go)\n\n**Parser functions:**\n- `Parse(input string)` - Generic parser\n- `ParseForContainer(input)` - Container workflow with location validation\n- `ParseForHost(input)` - Single host workflow\n- `ParseAllForHost(input)` - Multiple workflows in host.cloche\n\n**Parsing features:**\n- Step type inference from `prompt`/`run`/`workflow_name`\n- Workflow-level config blocks (`container {}`, `host {}`)\n- Step-level container blocks (`container { image = \"...\", network_allow = [...] }`)\n- Nested step field parsing with prefix composition (e.g., `container.image`)\n- Output mapping parsing with path expressions\n- Collect parsing with `all`/`any` modes\n- Validation: no orphaned steps, all results wired, location-appropriate step types\n\n### 6. Current Implementation Conventions\n\n**Workflow patterns:**\n1. **Linear workflow** - Sequential steps (hello-world/build.cloche)\n2. **Fanout + collect pattern** - Parallel checks then collect (ruby-calculator, gemini-browser, mini-redis all use this)\n3. **Retry loop** - Failure -> fix step -> retry test (all examples)\n4. **Host orchestration** - Host workflow dispatches container workflows via `workflow_name` steps\n\n**Standard step names observed:**\n- `implement` - Agent step for code generation\n- `test` - Script step for testing\n- `lint` / `clippy` / `rubocop` - Script steps for linting\n- `fmt` / `quality` - Script steps for formatting/quality checks\n- `fix` - Agent step for fixing failures\n- `design` - Agent step for architecture/design (some projects)\n- `prepare-prompt` - Script step for prompt preparation (host workflows)\n- `develop` - Workflow step dispatching container workflow (host workflows)\n\n**Result naming conventions:**\n- `success`, `fail` - Most common\n- `give-up` - When max_attempts exceeded\n- Step-specific results (e.g., `pass`, `retry_with_feedback`)\n\n### 7. Test Fixtures and Integration Examples\n\n**Key test cases in parser_test.go:**\n- `TestParser_FullWorkflow` - Complete workflow with agent and script steps\n- `TestParser_CollectAll` - Parallel fanout with `collect all()` convergence\n- `TestParser_CollectAny` - Race condition with `collect any()`\n- `TestParser_WorkflowNameStep` - Host workflow dispatching container workflow\n- `TestParser_WorkflowNameWithPromptStep` - Workflow step with `prompt_step` parameter\n- `TestParser_InfersTypeFromContent` - Step type inference\n- `TestParser_AmbiguousStepType` - Error on multiple step types\n\n**Example fanout pattern from ruby-calculator/develop.cloche:**\n```\ntest:success -> lint\ntest:success -> quality\nlint:fail -> fix\nquality:fail -> fix\ncollect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n```\n\n### 8. Container Setup and Dockerfiles\n\n**Pattern observed:**\n- Most examples use a language-specific base (rust, debian + build tools)\n- All copy `cloche-agent` binary from `cloche-agent:latest` build\n- All install Claude Code via npm: `npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`\n- Root project Dockerfile extends `cloche-base:latest` and adds language runtimes\n\n**Key conventions:**\n- Non-root `agent` user for security\n- `/workspace` as working directory (project root copied here at runtime)\n- Network isolation by default (`--network none`), allowlist via `network_allow` config\n\n### 9. System Design Document Summary\n\n**Three binaries:**\n- `cloche` - CLI client (run, status, logs, stop)\n- `cloched` - Daemon (container lifecycle, state persistence, gRPC API)\n- `cloche-agent` - In-container autonomous executor (parses DSL, walks graph)\n\n**Hexagonal architecture:**\n- Domain (Workflow, Step, Run types) is infrastructure-agnostic\n- Ports define interfaces (ContainerRuntime, RunStore, AgentAdapter)\n- Adapters implement concrete backends (Docker, SQLite, gRPC)\n\n**Container lifecycle:**\n- One container per workflow run\n- Project files copied to `/workspace/`\n- Results extracted via git branches per run\n- All steps in same container (file state accumulates naturally)\n\n### 10. Latest Conventions Summary\n\n**The current \"latest\" conventions are:**\n\n1. **Fanout + Collect for parallel validation**: Use `collect all()` or `collect any()` rather than sequential checking\n2. **Prompt template pattern**: Store templates in `prompts/` subdirectory and reference via `file(\"prompts/xxx.md\")`\n3. **Script step naming**: Verb-based names like `test`, `lint`, `fmt`, `quality`\n4. **Result naming**: Prefer `success`/`fail` with optional `give-up` for retryable steps\n5. **Max attempts**: Specify `max_attempts = \"N\"` on fix/retry steps\n6. **Host workflow structure**: Three-phase model (list-tasks, main, finalize) for task-driven orchestration\n7. **Agent command configuration**: Specify at workflow-level in `host {}` or `container {}` blocks\n8. **Network security**: Use `network_allow = [...]` lists instead of default open networking\n9. **Output mapping**: Use path expressions like `output.field` or `output[0].name` for inter-step communication\n10. **Step type clarity**: Explicitly declare results for each step, let inference handle type determination\n\nAll file paths are absolute as requested and this represents a comprehensive read-only exploration of the project structure and conventions."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ac63ab0110c3e51e5 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 55501\ntool_uses: 35\nduration_ms: 87038</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38a7cbbe-0157-40c7-bcaa-fa1bfb56d343","uuid":"59de2c95-95d1-423b-9124-83d728bbfb3c","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need to understand the current project structure, conventions, and what examples exist. Please do a very thorough exploration:\n\n1. List all files under examples/ directory recursively\n2. List all files under .cloche/ at the project root (if it exists)\n3. Read the workflow DSL documentation at docs/workflows.md\n4. Read any relevant docs about the current implementation conventions\n5. Look at the domain types for workflows - especially internal/domain/ to understand Step types, Result types, etc.\n6. Look at how workflows are parsed - find the workflow parser code\n7. Look at any test fixtures or integration test workflows that show the \"current\" expected format\n8. Read the Dockerfile conventions used in .cloche/\n9. Check docs/plans/2026-02-20-cloche-system-design.md for relevant context\n\nFocus on understanding what the \"latest conventions\" are so we can compare against the examples.","agentId":"ac63ab0110c3e51e5","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have a comprehensive understanding. Let me create the final report:\n\n## Thorough Project Exploration Report\n\nI have completed a comprehensive exploration of the Cloche project structure, conventions, and examples. Here's what I found:\n\n### 1. Project Files Under examples/ Directory\n\n**Examples present:**\n- `/workspace/examples/hello-world/` - Simple demonstration with build and flaky workflows\n- `/workspace/examples/ruby-calculator/` - Ruby project with implement/fix workflow\n- `/workspace/examples/gemini-browser/` - Rust project with design/implement workflow\n- `/workspace/examples/mini-redis/` - C project with design/implement workflow\n\n**Key files in each example:**\n- `develop.cloche` - Container workflow definition\n- `prompts/` - Prompt templates (implement.md, fix.md, design.md)\n- `scripts/` - Optional helper scripts (quality-check.py, etc.)\n- `Dockerfile` - Container image definition\n- `README.md` - Project documentation\n\n### 2. .cloche/ Directory at Project Root\n\nLocated at `/workspace/.cloche/`, the actual Cloche system's own workflows contain:\n- `develop.cloche` - Container workflow for the Cloche system itself\n- `host.cloche` - Host orchestration workflow with three phases (main)\n- `Dockerfile` - Base image extending `cloche-base:latest`\n- `attempt_count/` - Directory tracking retry attempts\n- `evolution/` - Snapshots of evolved workflows\n- `prompts/` - Prompt templates (implement.md, update-docs.md, fix.md)\n- `scripts/` - Host scripts (ready-tasks.sh, claim-task.sh, prepare-prompt.sh, merge-to-main.sh, cleanup-run.sh)\n- `history.log` - Execution history\n- 